Yes, the smart contract code is vulnerable. The vulnerability lies in the Collect function:

```
function Collect(uint _am)
public
payable
{
    var acc = Acc[msg.sender];
    if( acc.balance>=MinSum && acc.balance>=_am && now>acc.unlockTime)
    {

        if(msg.sender.call.value(_am)())
        {
            acc.balance-=_am;
            LogFile.AddMessage(msg.sender,_am,"Collect");
        }
    }
}
```

The `msg.sender.call.value(_am)()` line is the culprit. This allows for a reentrancy attack, as it allows the msg.sender to call an untrusted contract before the initial execution is complete. The contract state may change in the middle of its execution as a result of a call to an untrusted contract, leading to potential security issues.
